player.seasonOutlook: Dillon spent most of his rookie season buried behind Aaron Jones and Jamaal Williams (as expected), which limited him to 263 yards and a pair of TDs on 48 touches. Jones re-signed this offseason, which is bad news for Dillon's upside, but the departure of Williams opens the door for the 2020 second-round pick to play a much larger role. At 6-foot, 247 pounds, the Boston College product is one of the league's biggest backs and he's also extremely athletic for his size (4.53 40-yard dash). The big concern with Dillon is his passing-game limitations (21 receptions in 35 games at BC), but perhaps he can offset some of that with big plays and high-value goal line carries. Dillon is a good bench hold and would leap into the RB2 mix (at least) if Jones were to miss time.

Conner signed with Arizona after spending his first four seasons with the Steelers. The 2017 third-round pick has missed at least three games each of the past three seasons and a total of 14 in his career. The Pitt product peaked with an RB6 fantasy finish in 2018, but he plummeted outside the top 25 each of the past two seasons. The 26-year-old is solid as both a rusher (career 4.3 YPC, 1.8 YAC) and receiver (6.3 YPT), but figures to focus primarily on the former as he takes over Kenyan Drake's role in Arizona. Drake ranked seventh among RBs in carries, eighth in rush TDs and third in carries inside the 5-yard line in 2020. Conner will defer most passing-down work to Chase Edmonds, but his new role keeps him in the RB3/flex mix.

The Jets selected Carter in the fourth round of April's draft. The North Carolina product is on the small side at 5-foot-8, 201 pounds, but is quick, explosive and a terrific pass catching prospect. Carter was very effective in 2020, averaging 8.0 YPC and running for 10-plus yards on 23% of his carries (both best in this year's class). Carter's lack of size and speed could limit him to a change-of-pace/kick returner role in the pros, but he has a path to lead back duties in New York with Tevin Coleman and La'Mical Perine his top competition. Carter's pass-catching prowess and path to a big snap share launches him into immediate weekly flex consideration.

Williams signed with the Lions after spending his first four NFL seasons with the Packers. The 2017 fourth-round pick spent most of his Green Bay tenure in a situational role, maxing out at a 48% snap share in 2018 while averaging 125.0 carries and 38.3 targets per season. Williams is expected to play a similar role in Detroit, operating as a change-of-pace option behind D'Andre Swift. Williams' efficiency has generally been pedestrian at best and he's yet to finish a season better than 32nd in fantasy points. Williams won't have standalone value, but, if Swift were to miss time, the 26-year-old would lead the backfield and could push for RB2 production.

Goedert played at least 80% of the Eagles' snaps in nine games last season. He handled a 19% target share (6.8 per game) those weeks and a 42-479-3 receiving line was enough for the third-most fantasy points at the position. Goedert missed five games due to injury, which limited his overall output, but he's now finished top-11 in fantasy PPG each of the past two seasons. He enters his fourth NFL season in a new (albeit still TE-friendly) scheme and appears to have taken the team's No. 1 TE gig away from Zach Ertz. The 26-year-old is positioned as an every-down player in an offense that has one of the league's most inexperienced WR rooms. Consider Goedert a mid-to-back-end TE1.

Tonyan enjoyed a breakout season in 2020, posting a 52-586-11 receiving line on the way to finishing as fantasy's No. 4-scoring TE. He's 2021's "regression to the mean" Poster Boy, however, as his 59 targets tied for fewest by a top-12 fantasy TE over the past 12 seasons. Tonyan also paced TEs with an 88% catch rate and 18.6% TD rate, both of which aren't close to sustainable. Incredibly, Tonyan averaged 3.7 targets per game and failed to see more than six in a single game. With his rate stats bound to regress (some significantly), his volume will need to increase in 2021. The 27-year-old should be viewed as a TD-dependent, back-end TE1 who could easily fall back to TE2 territory.

Smith signed a four-year, $50 million contract with New England after spending his first four seasons in Tennessee. Smith's 65 targets, 41 receptions and 448 yards last season were career highs, though none ranked better than 17th at the position. He scored nine TDs, but was a bit lucky (6.6 OTD) and totaled eight (4.7 OTD) during his first three seasons. Smith's game is post-catch production, as he's ranked no lower than seventh at TE in RAC each of the past three seasons. He has never finished a season as a top-15 TE and may have trouble hitting that mark with Hunter Henry also on New England's roster (since 2009, only two sets of teammates posted a top-10 fantasy TE campaign in the same season). The 26-year-old is best-valued as a TE2.

Gesicki is technically a tight endï¿½but really he's a wide receiver. Last season, he aligned in the slot on 70% of his routes, out wide on 19% and was in line only 11% of the time for the Dolphins. The fantasy-friendly role allowed him a career-best 53-703-6 receiving line and seventh-place finish in fantasy points. However, a deeper look suggests he performed more like a TE2 than a TE1, amassing only four top-10 weeks, while finishing outside the top-20 five times. But there are plusses. He's handled exactly 11 end zone targets and has ranked top-four in aDOT each of the past two seasons. The 25-year-old has more competition for targets in the form of Will Fuller V and Jaylen Waddle this season, but his role is enough to allow fringe TE1 production, especially in non-PPR.

Brady's first season with Tampa Bay resulted in a top-3 finish among QBs in pass attempts, passing yards and touchdowns, his best fantasy campaign since 2017 (eighth) and another Super Bowl MVP trophy. Is that good? It seems good. Brady's numbers benefit from Tampa Bay's pass-heavy scheme and he has an outstanding supporting cast led by Mike Evans, Chris Godwin, Antonio Brown and Rob Gronkowski, but note that minimal contributions with his legs barely allowed him to crack the top 10 in fantasy points in 2020. It's fair to wonder if he'll be able to sustain weekly QB1 numbers if his passing production slips even slightly, but the 44-year-old nonetheless remains a fringe starter.

Jones is entering his fourth NFL season having established himself as an effective rusher, but finds himself without a clear lead back role. The 2018 second-round pick shared the backfield with Leonard Fournette in 2020, with the duo playing 12 "full" games together. During those outings, Jones trailed his teammate in snaps (419 to 296) and targets (56 to 23), but led in carries (132 to 114). Jones has shown to be the better rusher of the two (his 5.1 YPC ranked seventh and his 2.4 YAC fourth among RBs), but Fournette isn't going away and Giovani Bernard is now in the mix for passing-down work. Jones will max out as a flex most weeks, but the 24-year-old is a very good insurance option in Tampa Bay's high-scoring offense.

Sermon was selected by the 49ers in the third round of April's draft. The Ohio State standout is a big (6-foot, 215 pounds) and explosive runner who racked up 455 carries during three seasons at Oklahoma and one at OSU. Sermon sports a good elusiveness profile (top-10 in this class in both YAC and Forced Missed Tackle rate over the past three seasons), but lacks speed and his potential passing-game contributions are a question mark (he totaled 48 receptions and caught a weak 79% of his targets from 2018-20). Sermon has a shot to eventually emerge as the 49ers' lead back, but he'll first need to overtake Raheem Mostert and perhaps Jeff Wilson Jr. and Wayne Gallman. Sermon lacks standalone value in the short term, but he's a strong target for a bench stash considering Mostert's durability woes.

Hines has carved out a role as a solid change-of-pace and receiving back during his three NFL seasons. The 2018 fourth-round pick ranks sixth among RBs in targets (217), receptions (170) and receiving yards (1227) since he entered the league, though his 5-foot-8, 198-pound frame has limited him to 226 carries (50th-most) and a weak 4.0 YPC during the same timeframe. Hines posted a career-best 15th-place finish in fantasy points last season, but his already-small role as a rusher, especially at the goal line, may shrink further with Jonathan Taylor emerging into a superstar and Marlon Mack back healthy. Hines has some deep-league PPR flex appeal, but that's about where the 24-year-old maxes out.

Lindsay is now with the Texans after progressively falling out of favor during three seasons in Denver. The speedy and explosive Lindsay appeared to be a gem UDFA find by the Broncos back in 2018, having racked up 1,278 yards and 10 TDs on 227 touches as a rookie (he was RB13 in fantasy). However, a closer look showed an unsustainable pace in the TD and yardage departments and Lindsay's efficiency fell off in 2019 (still a solid RB19 fantasy campaign) before he was replaced by Melvin Gordon III atop the depth chart in 2020. The 27-year-old has struggled after contact throughout his career (1.4 YAC) and as a receiver (4.2 YPT), but is a fine change-of-pace option. He'll join the flex radar only if 29-year-old David Johnson misses time.

Hurts is locked in as the Eagles' starter after Carson Wentz was traded to the Colts. Hurts appeared in three full games as a rookie, throwing for 847 yards and five TDs, while adding a 38/238/1 rushing line, outscoring all but two QBs in that short span. Hurts' efficiency will need to improve, though his 52% completion rate was distorted by a league-high 9.5 average depth of throw (the longer the pass, the lower the expected completion rate) and his 13.8 YPC paced the NFL, hinting at a worthwhile tradeoff. Hurts will need to overcome a shaky and/or unproven group of targets, but he has a very good line and his elite rushing provides a high weekly floor. Consider the 23-year-old a borderline QB1.

Tannehill took over as the Titans' starting QB in Week 7 of the 2019 season. He was fantasy's No. 3 QB from that point forward and followed that up by finishing seventh as the full-time starter in 2020. He's been nothing short of elite during the two campaigns, totaling 66 TDs and 13 INTs while completing 67% of his passes and averaging a league-best 8.6 YPA. The addition of Julio Jones helps offset the departures of Corey Davis, Jonnu Smith and Adam Humphries, but losing OC Arthur Smith is notable as well. This still figures to be a very run-heavy offense (Tannehill finished 18th in pass attempts last season), which limits the ceiling a bit. Even at 33 years old, Tannehill still adds value with his legs, which along with his strong efficiency, keeps him in the QB1 conversation.

Stafford was traded to the Rams during the offseason following 12 seasons in Detroit. The 33-year-old is eyeing a bounce-back campaign; Although Stafford finished as a top-nine fantasy QB six times in the past decade, he hasn't done so since 2017. Stafford's fantasy upside is certainty limited by a lack of rushing contributions (347 rush yards and 0 TDs over the past four years), but his passing production and efficiency is likely to improve under Sean McVay and with a Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp at his disposal. Note that Stafford has ranked top-3 in average depth of throw in each of the past two seasons. Consider Stafford a good QB2 option.

Beasley has emerged as one of the league's best and most reliable slot WRs during two seasons in Buffalo. He came through with a solid 67-778-6 receiving line and WR34 fantasy campaign in 2019. His target share dipped from 23% to 20% last season, but Buffalo's switch to a pass-heavy scheme boosted him to an 82-967-4 line and career-best WR27 fantasy showing. Beasley is now 32 years old and his short-range role limits his upside (he's never finished higher than the 17th percentile in aDOT), but he'll continue to be an underrated fantasy option if he remains Josh Allen's No. 2 target. And that's the expectation with John Brown out and Emmanuel Sanders in opposite Stefon Diggs. Consider Beasley for your flex in leagues with 12 or more teams.

Pittman missed three contests and was limited to 4.6 targets per game during a fairly uninspiring rookie campaign. The 2020 second-round pick was on the field for a hefty 78% of Indianapolis' offensive snaps when active, but he was held to a 40-503-1 receiving line and only two weekly fantasy finishes better than 50th. Pittman was mostly used in the short area (8.9 aDOT) but was terrific with the ball in his hands (his 6.9 RAC ranked third among WRs). The 23-year-old is a strong bet for a second-year leap as he slots in opposite T.Y. Hilton, with Parris Campbell in the slot. The 6-foot-4 Pittman is a breakout candidate and a very good late-flier for your bench.

Following a breakout 2019 campaign in which he posted a 72-1,202-9 receiving line en route to a WR11 fantasy campaign, Parker crashed back to earth in 2020. He missed two games, was held to a 63-793-4 line and finished 40th in fantasy points. He has now missed at least one game (13 total) and finished 40th or worse in fantasy points in five of his six seasons. Parker will have more competition for targets this season after Miami signed Will Fuller V and drafted Jaylen Waddle, and the team's QB situation is a question mark with unproven Tua Tagovailoa under center. The 28-year-old Parker will still play a sizable role, but there's enough risk here that he's best-valued as a flex option.

Meyers barely saw the field during his first year-plus in the league, but that changed when Julian Edelman went down for the season in Week 7 last season. Meyers took over and racked up 81 targets (a massive 30% team share) while playing 96% of the offensive snaps during the team's final 11 games. The 2019 UDFA signing was WR22 in fantasy during that stretch, bizarrely failing to catch a TD, but throwing two. Edelman retired, but Meyers has more competition for targets this season via newcomers Nelson Agholor, Kendrick Bourne, Hunter Henry and Jonnu Smith. Meyers struggled for fantasy relevance on last year's massive target share, so it's hard to imagine the 24-year-old joining the flex discussion in his current situation, especially in such a run-heavy scheme. Consider him for your bench in deep PPR formats.

The 2020 season was a rough one for the Eagles' offense, and that was highlighted by injuries and poor QB play. Both affected Reagor, as the rookie was limited to 11 games and 26% of balls thrown his direction were off target (fourth highest among WRs). The 2020 first-round pick ended up with a 31-396-1 receiving line and zero top-30 fantasy weeks. On the plus side, the scheme and QB will be different (albeit unproven) this season, and Reagor, whose 5.7 RAC ranked 11th among WRs, is likely to play an every-down role opposite rookie De'Vonta Smith. Reagor will see consistent targets in an offense lacking weapons and that will likely be throwing often in the second half of games. The 22-year-old is a logical post-hype breakout candidate and good mid-round target.

Following an impressive showing as a third-round rookie in 2019, Singletary appeared to be on the verge of a second-year breakout. Instead, Buffalo drafted Zack Moss, moved to a pass-heavy scheme and limited Singletary to a committee role. Despite ranking 10th among RBs in snaps last season, Singletary finished outside the Top 20 in touches and yards while scoring only two TDs. Incredibly, Singletary's best weekly fantasy finish was 15th and he was outside the top 30 in 10 of 16 games. In 14 games together, Singletary held the edge over Moss in snaps (482 to 397) and targets (43 to 24), but trailed in carries (119 to 117). Singletary is a solid player, but his role is unlikely to expand with Moss in the mix. The 24-year-old is a fine bench option with some deep league flex appeal.

Johnson was better than it seemed last season, delivering a top-10 fantasy showing in 33% of his games (ninth-best) and falling outside the top-30 only once in 11 full games. He played 81% of Houston's snaps, averaging 13.2 carries and 4.1 targets per game, which allowed him the seventh-most fantasy points during the 11 weeks. His rushing efficiency was good (4.70 YPC, 1.88 YAC) and his receiving efficiency was elite (his 6.8 YPT ranked fifth among RBs -- his fourth-career top-six finish in the category). Johnson is now 29 years old and the Houston offense has some uncertainty with Deshaun Watson's future in question, but he remains the lead back ahead of Philip Lindsay and Mark Ingram. Expect Johnson to flirt with RB2 numbers.

Williams is now with Detroit after missing the entire 2020 season with a torn labrum. The 2015 UDFA looked like a gem find by the Chargers when he posted a 69-1,059-7 receiving line and was WR18 in fantasy back in 2016. However, despite settling in as a respectable vertical threat (finished top-15 in YPT in four consecutive seasons), Williams hasn't posted a fantasy finish better than 45th since. Williams is positioned for a full-time role in rebuilding Detroit, which certainly makes the 29-year-old a deep sleeper. Even in an offense that should struggle in 2021, Williams is worth a late flier.

The Colts selected Campbell in the second round of the 2019 draft, but the Ohio State product has appeared in nine of a possible 32 games due to injury. Campbell barely saw the field as a rookie (22 touches in seven games) but appeared to be on the verge of a breakout in 2020. Campbell played 83% of the snaps in Week 1 and put up 80 yards on seven touches before going down for the season in Week 2. Campbell remains a very intriguing post-hype sleeper, especially considering T.Y. Hilton is now 31 years old and Michael Pittman Jr. is an unproven commodity. Campbell is super fast (a 4.31 40-yard dash) and quick (a 4.03 short shuttle) with the ability to contribute from the slot, as a rusher and as a returner. Grab him for your bench.

Hilton re-signed with the Colts and will be looking for a bounce-back campaign after finishing outside the top-40 fantasy WRs each of the past two seasons. Hilton's 2020 was a tale of two seasons, as he posted an ugly 29-327-0 line on 30 targets and was WR85 in fantasy through nine games before exploding for a 27-435-5 line on 42 targets (WR11 in fantasy) over his final six games. Hilton averaged 6.1 targets per game for the season (his lowest since his rookie season in 2012), and he has now missed at least one game each of the past three seasons (nine total). The 31-year-old will have another new QB (Carson Wentz) this season, and youngsters Michael Pittman Jr. and Parris Campbell are candidates for expanded roles. Hilton is best viewed as a flex.

Hardman is an occasional contributor in one of the league's best and highest-volume pass offenses, but the 2019 second-round pick simply has not seen enough volume to warrant fantasy consideration. Hardman has flashed playmaking ability (his 8.7 RAC ranks second among WRs since he was drafted) but didn't see the field much as a rookie (41 targets on 429 snaps) and barely saw an increase in 2020 (62 targets on 475 snaps). Perhaps the 24-year-old will finally be promoted into a starting gig opposite Tyreek Hill in 2021, but we can't count on that with Demarcus Robinson, intriguing Byron Pringle and rookie Cornell Powell in the fold. Hardman shouldn't be in early-season lineups, but he's a very good lottery ticket for your bench.

Mooney was the 24th wide receiver selected in the 2020 draft, but the unheralded fifth-rounder ended his rookie campaign seventh in the class in targets and ninth in fantasy points. Mooney quickly locked down Chicago's No. 2 WR gig opposite Allen Robinson and ended up with a solid 61-631-4 line on 98 targets. Mooney's 61 receptions are tied with Tyreek Hill for fourth most all-time by a rookie not drafted in the first four rounds. His efficiency was poor (his 6.4 YPT was seventh lowest among 87 qualified WRs), but poor QB play was a major factor, as 23% of balls thrown his way were off target (14th highest). Mooney will play a similar - if not expanded - role in the same scheme with perhaps better QB play in 2021. Take a late flier.

During the final five weeks of 2019, Higbee came out of nowhere to average 11.4 targets per game and was fantasy's top-scoring TE by 23 points. It appeared the cat was out of the bag and Higbee was finally in the TE1 mix. So much for that. Higbee posted a 44-521-5 receiving line in 2020 with three of those five scores coming in one game (he had a 43-522-2 line during those five weeks in 2019). Higbee is a good all-around player, but he's now 28 years old and Sean McVay doesn't seem interested in permanently increasing his passing-game usage. Perhaps Matthew Stafford will unlock his fantasy value, but even with Gerald Everett is gone, Higbee is an uninspiring TE2.

Engram was the No. 5-scoring fantasy TE as a rookie in 2017, but hasn't been able to match that success in three seasons since. The former first-round pick ranked seventh in fantasy PPG in both 2018 and 2019, but missed 13 games during the span. In 2020, he finally appeared in 16 games and finished no lower than sixth in routes, targets and receptions, but his efficiency plummeted, which left him with a 15th-place fantasy showing. Engram scored six TDs as a rookie, but has seven total the past three seasons. He led all TEs in drops (eight) and was near the basement in catch rate and YPT in 2020. Engram's raw skills supply him with upside, but after his 2020 struggles and with Kenny Golladay, Kadarius Toney and Kyle Rudolph now in the mix, the 27-year-old is best-viewed as a good TE2.

Hooper is entering his second season in Cleveland after failing to manage a top-20 fantasy campaign in 2020. The 2016 third-round pick had finished sixth in fantasy points in both 2018 and 2019 and actually averaged a career-high 19% target share in 2020, but Cleveland's run-first scheme severely limited his volume and production. Hooper was primarily used as a short-area target (6.8 aDOT), which limited him to a career-low 6.3 YPT, and failed to clear four TDs for the fourth time in five seasons. Hooper did finish strong with three consecutive top-eight fantasy weeks, but it's hard to imagine that sustains into 2021 in the same scheme with Odell Beckham Jr. back from injury. Hooper is a low-ceiling TE2.

The phrase "volume is king" isn't often applied to quarterbacks, but it fits the bill when breaking down Burrow's rookie campaign. The 2020 first overall pick went down for the season in Week 11, but prior to that, he ranked first among QBs in snaps and drop backs, second in pass attempts, ninth in passing yards and 14th in fantasy points. Burrow's efficiency (65%, 6.7 YPA) was solid as far as rookie QBs go and he added value with his legs (37-142-2 rushing line). Burrow is an obvious candidate for a second-year leap and has a good core of targets in Ja'Marr Chase, Tee Higgins, Tyler Boyd and Joe Mixon. Consider him a good QB2.

Tagovailoa is now the clear-cut starter in Miami following Ryan Fitzpatrick's offseason departure. The 2020 fifth-overall pick was in and out of the lineup during a bumpy rookie campaign, but ended up with 14 total TDs to five INTs and was QB15 in fantasy points during seven full games as a rookie. Tagovailoa's efficiency will need to improve, but he adds some value with his legs and has an improved supporting cast after Will Fuller V and Jaylen Waddle were added to a core that also includes DeVante Parker and Mike Gesicki. Tagovailoa isn't a sure thing, but he's well-positioned for a second-year breakout and shouldn't cost more than a late-round flier on draft day.

Lawrence was selected by Jacksonville with the first overall pick of April's draft. The Clemson product is an athletic 6-foot-5, 213 pounds with an outstanding arm. Lawrence's FBS passing efficiency stats don't jump off the page, but that shouldn't undermine his high-end potential, especially considering that his raw stats were incredible (90 TDs, 17 INTs in 40 games). Adding to Lawrence's appeal is his mobility, as he ran for 776 yards and 17 TDs over the past two seasons. Rookie QBs are rarely reliable fantasy starters, but Lawrence's mobility and a good group of targets led by DJ Chark, Laviska Shenault Jr., Marvin Jones Jr. and James Robinson gives him a shot to be an exception. He's worth a mid-to-late flier and obviously has QB1 upside in dynasty leagues.

Sometimes situation rules all and that was the case for McKissic in 2020. The journeyman scat back latched on with Washington as a complement to Antonio Gibson and went on to lead all running backs in routes (385) and targets (111), while finishing second in receptions (80) and receiving yards (589). McKissic played a much lesser role as a rusher (85-365-1), but his massive receiving role allowed him a 17th-place finish in fantasy points. It was his first finish better than 49th since he entered the league as a UDFA in 2016. McKissic's role figures to decline as Gibson's increases and new QB Ryan Fitzpatrick is sure to lean less on dumpoff throws than Alex Smith did, but the 27-year-old will remain involved in obvious passing situations. Consider him for your bench in deep PPR leagues, but the ceiling is low.

The 2020 season was White's first without Tom Brady and, not coincidentally, it resulted in his worst fantasy finish (42nd) since a 2014 rookie campaign in which he touched the ball 14 times. Despite the dud, White quietly ranked fourth at RB with a 16% target share (4.4 per game) and has been at or above 16% each of the past three seasons. He's finished no lower than 11th at RB in targets, receptions and receiving yards each of the past five seasons, but had 35 carries in 2020 and has never cleared 95 in a single season. The 29-year-old will defer nearly all rushing work to Damien Harris and Rhamondre Stevenson, but his huge receiving role keeps him in the deep league PPR flex discussion.

Brown signed with the Dolphins after spending the first six seasons of his career with the Rams. The 2015 UDFA easily set career-high marks in carries (110), rushing yardage (449), targets (35), receptions (25) and receiving yards (175) last season, but a lot of that damage was done during his only two top-20 fantasy weeks. Brown has scored five TDs each of the past two seasons, but has yet to finish a season as a top-40 fantasy RB. The 28-year-old figures to handle the occasional touch while focusing on special teams in Miami and would need at least one injury (perhaps two) to join the RB2 mix. He does not need to be drafted.

Pollard has impressed since being selected to serve Ezekiel Elliott's backup in the fourth round of the 2019 draft. After pacing the league in YAC (2.7) on 86 rookie-season carries, Pollard saw his numbers come back to earth this past season, but he still managed a serviceable 435 yards on 101 carries. Pollard has played more than 47% of Dallas' snaps only once - a 2020 Week 15 game in which Elliott was sidelined. Pollard was fantasy's top-scoring RB that week, producing 69 yards and 2 TDs on 12 carries and 63 yards on nine targets. Pollard lacks standalone value behind a healthy Elliott, but the high-volume Dallas offense is absolutely loaded in 2021, making the 24-year-old Pollard an elite insurance option.

Minnesota selected Mattison in the third round of the 2019 draft and the former Boise State star has done an admirable job backing up Dalvin Cook over the past two seasons (4.6 YPC, 1.9 YAC, 7.7 YPT). Mattison doesn't see the field much when Cook is healthy, but showed well with 277 yards and three TDs on 58 touches in three games in relief of an injured Cook in 2020. Only six RBs scored more fantasy points those weeks. Mattison has no standalone value, but especially after the departure of Mike Boone, the 23-year-old is locked in as one of fantasy's top insurance options. He'll be in the RB1 discussion if Cook (two-plus missed games in all four NFL seasons) misses more time.

Hyde is now on his second stop in Jacksonville after battling for work in Kansas City, Houston and Seattle the past two years. Hyde's first stop in Jacksonville was unsuccessful (62 touches in eight games in 2018), but that was, of course, a different regime, as the team has now hired Hyde's college coach, Urban Meyer. Hyde, who turns 30 this year, adds little as a receiver and is no longer feature back material, but makes for a solid backup. That's the role he's likely to play behind James Robinson this season. Hyde will only be on the fantasy radar if Robinson misses time.

Henry signed with New England after five seasons with the Chargers. The 2016 second-round pick is coming off back-to-back top-12 fantasy campaigns despite missing six games during the stretch. Durability has been a major problem area for Henry, as he's yet to manage a 16-game season in his career. Henry finished eighth among TEs in targets and receptions last season, but his volume is likely to decrease this season with Jonnu Smith also on the depth chart. Whereas Smith is a short-area/RAC weapon, Henry has done a lot of his damage downfield, so perhaps he'll hit for the occasional big play. Of course, considering the Patriots' run-heavy scheme and how rare it is for one team to produce two fantasy relevant TEs, Henry will be hard to trust as anything more than a mid-to-back-end TE2.

Gronkowski made a triumphant return to the NFL last season, appearing in all 20 of Tampa Bay's games en route to a Super Bowl victory. During the regular season, Gronkowski lacked targets (4.8 per game), but made up for it (as usual) with downfield usage (he's finished all 10 of his seasons Top 10 in aDOT) and heavy volume near the goal line (he paced the position with 14 end zone targets). Gronkowski's routine disappearing act last season (six top-six fantasy weeks, but eight of 23rd or worse), coupled with the return of O.J. Howard (who out-targeted him 19 to 14 in four games together last season), suggests we should view the 32-year-old as a TD-dependent TE2.

Smith is entering his third NFL season and is finally positioned for a breakout following the offseason departure of Kyle Rudolph. Smith has thus far been limited to 91 targets in 29 regular season games (3.1 per game) and has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy season. With Rudolph sidelined during the final four weeks of 2020, Smith posted a strong 15-183-3 receiving line and was TE4 in fantasy, though he was out-targeted 22-to-20 by Tyler Conklin. Aside of the boost in opportunity in a high-scoring Vikings offense, the biggest reason for optimism with Smith may be his age, as the 2019 second-round pick turns 23 in August. Smith is a strong TE2 target with room for more.

Mayfield and the Browns took a big step forward in 2020, but the team's success did not lead to much fantasy production for Mayfield. Leading Kevin Stefanski's run-heavy scheme, Mayfield ranked 17th in pass attempts, 18th in passing yards and 14th in total TDs (27) while finishing outside the top 15 in fantasy points for the third consecutive season. Mayfield finished a week better than 10th only three times in 16 tries. The 26-year-old will benefit from the return of Odell Beckham Jr., but adds very little with his legs and will continue to hand off the ball often, especially after the team made major defensive upgrades. He's a back-end QB2.

Fields was selected by Chicago with the 11th overall pick of April's draft. The Ohio State product checks in at 6-foot-3, 227 pounds with outstanding accuracy, a good arm and high-end rushing ability. The latter sets him apart (81-383-5 rushing line in 2020), but Fields has also shown to be an aggressive and effective passer. His 10.3 average depth of throw and 91 total QBR are both tops in this year's rookie class over the past three seasons and he protected the ball well (1.5% INT rate). It's possible Andy Dalton will get a few starts to open 2021, but the history of first-round QBs suggests Fields will be under center very quickly. His elite rushing ability, powered by 4.45 wheels, could quickly launch him into fantasy relevance, so he'll be a fine late-round pick.

Lance was selected by the 49ers with the third overall pick of April's draft. The North Dakota State product has a solid frame at 6-foot-4, 224 pounds and his best assets are his huge arm and rushing ability. N.D. State didn't play in 2020 due to COVID, but Lance threw for 2,789 yards (9.7 YPA) and ran for 1,110 (6.5 YPC) in 16 games in 2019. Lance's shaky accuracy and a severe lack of experience (one full season as starter, 17.9 pass attempts per game) are concern areas, but his combination of size, arm talent and rushing ability supplies plenty of upside. Lance may not start early on, but it's only a matter of time until he overtakes Jimmy Garoppolo. With a good supporting cast and Kyle Shanahan running the show, Lance will have some fantasy appeal, so he's worth late-round consideration.

Ryan returns for his 14th season with the Falcons, though things figure to look a bit different this time around. Ryan has finished no lower than third in pass attempts each of the past three seasons and has finished top-10 in completions and passing yards each of the past 11 seasons. However, new head coach Arthur Smith's Tennessee offense ranked 31st in attempts and 21st in passing yards during his two-year tenure. On the plus side, Ryan has managed only one top-10 fantasy campaign over the past four years, whereas Smith's QBs ranked top-10 in both 2019 and 2020. Ryan adds very little with his legs and that won't change at age-36, so with a dip in volume, no Julio Jones and perhaps a boost in efficiency, he's, at best, a mid-range fantasy QB2.

The Jets selected Moore with the 34th pick of April's draft. The Ole Miss product is an athletic 5-foot-9, 185-pound slot receiver with good speed and quickness. He has reliable hands and post-catch tackle-breaking ability but can also get deep for a big play. His size may limit his ability to play outside and beat press, but he has the look of a high-volume slot target who can help out as a rusher and returner. He aligned inside 92% of the time and handled a healthy 27% target share while posting a 91% adjusted catch rate during his final three FBS seasons. Moore's 2021 fantasy outlook is clouded by a rookie QB (Zach Wilson) and a very crowded WR room (Jamison Crowder, Corey Davis, Denzel Mims, Keelan Cole), but his pedigree makes him well worth a late-round flier.
